# TypeScript Rules

## Type Safety
- Always use TypeScript types, avoid `any` unless absolutely necessary
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` when type is truly unknown
- Define explicit types for function parameters and return values
- Use type inference only when types are obvious from context

## Type Definitions
- Define types in `types/` directory within each entity/feature
- Use PascalCase for type names (`Request`, `User`, `Proposal`)
- Use `interface` for object shapes that might be extended
- Use `type` for unions, intersections, and computed types
- Export types from `index.ts` for public API

## Zod Schemas
- Always define Zod schemas for data validation
- Place schemas in `schemas/` directory
- Use schemas for:
  - API request/response validation
  - Form validation with React Hook Form
  - Runtime type checking
- Infer TypeScript types from Zod schemas using `z.infer<typeof schema>`

## Type Organization
- Group related types in the same file
- Use separate files for complex types (e.g., `types/requests/`, `types/responses/`)
- Re-export types through `index.ts` for clean imports

## Generic Types
- Use generics for reusable components and utilities
- Provide meaningful generic parameter names (e.g., `TData`, `TError`)
- Constrain generics when appropriate

## Type Guards
- Create type guard functions for runtime type checking
- Use type guards with Zod schemas for validation

## Import Types
- Use `import type` for type-only imports to improve build performance
- Example: `import type { Request } from '@entities/request'`

## Strict Mode
- The project uses relaxed TypeScript settings for flexibility
- Still aim for type safety where possible
- Document `any` usage with comments explaining why
